Since $P$ and $Q$ are points of tangency, $OP = OQ = r_1$ and $O_1P \perp PQ \perp O_2Q,$ so $O_1PQO_2$ is a rectangle.  Hence, $M$ is the midpoint of $\overline{O_1 O_2},$ so $OM = \frac{1}{2} O_1 O_2 = \sqrt{(17 - 2)^2 + (10 - 2)^2} = \sqrt{325}.$

Also, $O_1 P = O_2 Q = r_1,$ so
\[MP = O_1 M - O_1 P = \sqrt{OM^2 - O_1 P^2} - r_1 = \sqrt{325 - \frac{100}{5}} - \frac{10}{\sqrt{5}} = \frac{10 \sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{13}} - \frac{10}{\sqrt{5}}.\]Similarly, $MQ = O_2 M - O_2 Q = \sqrt{325 - \frac{100}{5}} - \frac{10}{\sqrt{5}} = \frac{10 \sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{13}} - \frac{10}{\sqrt{5}},$ so the distance between the closest points of the two circles is $PQ = 2 \cdot MP = \boxed{\frac{20 \sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{13}} - \frac{20}{\sqrt{5}}}.$
